function solve(nums) {
    // This problem asks for the maximum number of fixed points (where the element equals its index)
    // we can achieve after deleting any number of elements.
    // When elements are deleted, the remaining elements shift left, and indices are re-assigned.
    // If we keep a subsequence of the original array, say at original indices i_0, i_1, ..., i_{k-1},
    // the new array will be [nums[i_0], nums[i_1], ..., nums[i_{k-1}]].
    // A fixed point occurs at new index j if nums[i_j] == j.
    // We want to maximize the count of such j's.

    // Let's consider two elements at original indices i and j, where i < j.
    // If we keep both, and they end up at new indices p and q (with p < q),
    // then:
    // 1. For the first element (at original index i), if it's a fixed point, nums[i] = p.
    // 2. For the second element (at original index j), if it's a fixed point, nums[j] = q.
    // Since p and q are determined by how many elements before i and j were kept,
    // this suggests a dynamic programming or a greedy approach based on Longest Increasing Subsequence (LIS) ideas.

    // If we select a subsequence of indices i_0, i_1, ..., i_{k-1} such that i_0 < i_1 < ... < i_{k-1},
    // and we want the element at new index j (which is nums[i_j]) to be a fixed point,
    // we need nums[i_j] = j.

    // This means we are looking for the longest subsequence of indices i_0, i_1, ..., i_{k-1}
    // such that nums[i_j] = j for as many j as possible.

    // Let's rephrase: we want to select a set of original indices S = {i_0, i_1, ..., i_{k-1}}
    // with i_0 < i_1 < ... < i_{k-1} (and k = |S|),
    // such that the number of indices j (0 <= j < k) where nums[i_j] = j is maximized.

    // This is equivalent to finding the Longest Subsequence where the value at the j-th element of the subsequence
    // equals j.

    // We can use dynamic programming. Let dp[j] be the maximum number of fixed points we can achieve
    // if the last fixed point achieved corresponds to an element originally at index i, and this fixed point is at new index j.
    // This seems complicated because we don't know which original index 'i' maps to the fixed point at 'j'.

    // Simpler Greedy Approach / DP based on the target value:
    // We are trying to construct the longest sequence such that the j-th element of the sequence is equal to j.
    // We iterate through the original array `nums`. For each `nums[i]`, we want to see if we can use it
    // as the j-th element of our target sequence, where j = nums[i].

    // If we choose nums[i] to be the element that ends up at new index j = nums[i],
    // it means exactly j elements before nums[i] in the original array (at indices < i) must have been selected
    // to form the prefix of the sequence.

    // Let `count` be the length of the longest prefix subsequence we have successfully constructed so far,
    // where the j-th element of this subsequence satisfies nums[i_j] = j (for j < count).

    let fixedPoints = 0; // This tracks the required target index (j) for the *next* potential fixed point.
                          // If we have found fixed points for 0, 1, ..., fixedPoints-1,
                          // the next one we seek must satisfy nums[i_j] = fixedPoints.

    for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
        // If nums[i] is equal to the next required fixed point index (`fixedPoints`),
        // it means we can potentially select nums[i] to be the (fixedPoints)-th element
        // in our resulting sequence, and it will satisfy the fixed-point condition (value = index).
        if (nums[i] === fixedPoints) {
            // If we select nums[i], we successfully form a new fixed point at index `fixedPoints`.
            // We increment the count of fixed points found so far, and we look for the next one (fixedPoints + 1).
            fixedPoints++;
        }
    }

    // `fixedPoints` now holds the total number of successful matches found.
    return fixedPoints;
}

